The pizza market and housing market are both markets, so both work on market principles. The $10 pizzas will only outcompete $15 pizzas if other factors like the perceived quality of the pizzas are the same, or customer service, or whatever. If the cheaper pizzas are perceived as lower quality, then they may not outcompete the more expensive pizzas. It may very well be the case that there’s enough customer base to go around that both the $15 and $10 pizzas have enough revenue to operate indefinitely, and the same is true of housing. Potential renters and buyers can choose from cheaper housing in worse areas, or simply further away from their place of employment, or in the form of apartments rather than proper houses, etc, or they could go for more expensive options like free-standing houses in nice areas. Inevitably, both budget and expensive housing will coexist in relative proximity based on the needs and means of the customer base.

Anonymity is our base default.
I doubt this is the first post to inform you, so I feel less bad about being the bearer of bad news; I’ll just give it to you straight, as I see it at least.
Before cameras and computers with databases, it was (relatively) easy for someone to get away with having a fake name and identity.
Whether it be to flee unwanted child support cheques or on the run for murder, a lot of people, most people, would simply act on impulse to whatever desire.
The risk to reward ratio was (for 99.9% of history) in favour of the home invader rapist-muderer-monster.
Anonymity doesn’t ‘bring out the worst’ in people.
The worst of humanity is still here, right under the noses of regular folk. The regular folk, I estimate, is probably in the minority by the slimmest of margins.
You can see it almost everywhere if you look hard enough.
From the way law enforcement, to political campaigns, to civil rights/liberties function. You can roughly gather, with the right kind of eyes, that it’s all a fraud on its face, a sick caricature of freedom, choice, security.
Put there only to satiate the naive masses; and only the basic barebone essentials.
The worst are still out there, today we just have a sort of ‘code of conduct’ for degeneracy.
It goes roughly ‘1 don’t do anything against the perfect public image created for one’s self, and 2 don’t fuck with anyone of note, anyone that could retaliate’

TL;DR
anonymity doesn’t make us bad, constant surveillance through technology makes us fake; maybe even more violent when the tendency arrives.
You know others feel this way and can’t show it. It feels like the world is waiting for people like you to die off.

Online platforms let you post whatever, and mob mentality quickly takes over. All you can really tell is whether whatever they posted is inside or outside what you think is acceptable online behavior.

All anonymity really gives is the assurance the shit you are putting out unfiltered can’t be traced back to you.
